"""
mkt-context commentary — Leviticus 22–23 (77 verses)
Ch22: Priestly holiness and acceptable offerings — context in the Holiness Code
Ch23: The festival calendar (moadim) — ANE background, Second Temple practice,
      NT typological reception (Passover/Christ, Firstfruits/Resurrection, Pentecost/Spirit)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

LEVITICUS_CONTEXT = {
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 22 continues the regulations for the Aaronic priesthood begun in chapter 21. Where chapter 21 addressed the personal holiness requirements of priests (physical wholeness, marriage rules, mourning prohibitions), chapter 22 addresses functional holiness: when priests may eat the sacred donations and what quality of animal is acceptable for sacrifice. The chapter belongs to the Holiness Code (chs. 17-26), which repeatedly grounds Israel's distinctiveness in YHWH's own holiness ('I am YHWH who sanctifies you,' v.32). The priestly regulations here are the internal counterpart to the general Israelite food and purity laws of chapters 11-15.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The command that priests 'keep away from the holy things' when impure protects the integrity of the sacred donations (<em>qodashim</em>). The priestly house received portions of the offerings — the <em>terumah</em> (heave offering), the breast and right thigh of peace offerings, the unleavened bread from Nazirite offerings, and portions of grain offerings. These donations sustained the priestly family economically in exchange for their tabernacle service. The system of sacred donations was also a form of social security for the priestly tribe, which owned no land (Num 18:20-24). Malachi 1:6-14 shows how the system was abused when priests accepted inferior animals and treated the sacred donations with contempt.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The <em>karet</em> (cutting off) penalty for eating holy food while ritually impure appears here as in other crucial holiness violations. In context, the priest who eats sacred food while impure has treated the holy as common — this is precisely the profanation (<em>chillul</em>) that the Holiness Code most consistently condemns. Second Temple priestly practice included elaborate procedures for confirming ritual purity before eating <em>terumah</em>: handwashing, immersion, and waiting periods were all part of maintaining the system the Torah requires.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The specific impurity conditions that disqualify a priest from eating sacred donations — skin disease (<em>tzara'at</em>), genital discharge (<em>zob</em>), corpse-contamination — are the same major categories addressed in chapters 13-15. The cross-referential structure is deliberate: the purity-law block and the priestly-regulation block are designed to be read together. A reader who has absorbed chapters 11-15 already knows exactly what conditions the priest must avoid and how to resolve each one.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Contact impurity transmission: touching someone who transmits corpse-impurity, or a person with a discharge, makes the priest impure. The impurity-chain logic (person A touched corpse → person B touched A → person B is now impure) works through physical contact. Numbers 19 develops the corpse-impurity rules in detail with the red heifer purification. The Second Temple period saw vigorous debate about the specifics of impurity transmission — the Pharisees and Sadducees disagreed on many points of application.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The person who touches any such thing shall be unclean until the evening and shall not eat of the holy things unless he has bathed his body in water.' The resolution mechanism for most minor impurities — water immersion + evening — was the standard baseline. Later Jewish practice formalized this as the <em>mikveh</em> (ritual immersion pool), which became a standard installation in any Jewish community. The evening boundary (when a new day begins in Jewish reckoning) created a clean daily reset for ordinary impurities.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'When the sun goes down he shall be clean, and afterward he may eat of the holy things, for they are his food.' The priest's access to sacred donations is not a spiritual luxury but his sustenance — 'for they are his food.' The Levitical system created a labor-for-donations economy: priests served at the altar and in turn received portions of the offerings. Paul cites this principle directly: 'those who proclaim the gospel should get their living by the gospel' (1 Cor 9:13-14), explicitly drawing on the Levitical pattern.</p>",
    "8": "<p><em>Nevela</em> (animal that died naturally) and <em>trefah</em> (animal torn by predators) are prohibited to priests — a stricter standard than for ordinary Israelites, who could give such meat to foreigners (Deut 14:21). The priestly diet was a subset of the broader Israelite dietary laws: what was permissible for the laity was not necessarily permissible for priests. This graduated holiness — ordinary Israelites, Levites, priests, high priest — each with progressively stricter purity requirements — reflects the concentric structure of the tabernacle itself (courts, holy place, holy of holies).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'They shall therefore keep my charge, lest they bear sin for it and die thereby when they profane it.' The death penalty for priestly mishandling of holy things is not merely threatened but enacted in the narrative: Nadab and Abihu died for offering unauthorized fire (Lev 10:1-2); Uzzah died for touching the ark improperly (2 Sam 6:7). These narratives function as cautionary examples that make the abstract warning of v.9 concrete. The priestly vocation was both privilege and mortal risk.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The household boundary for eating <em>terumah</em>: <em>zar</em> (stranger/outsider) cannot eat it. The 'stranger' here is not necessarily a non-Israelite but anyone not part of the priestly household by birth or purchase. A resident worker (<em>toshav</em>) or hired laborer (<em>sakhir</em>) employed by the priest — who lives in the house but is not a member of the family — cannot eat the sacred donations. The priestly household is a religious unit with economic boundaries as well as kinship ones.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A slave purchased by a priest becomes a full member of the priestly household and may eat sacred donations; a slave born in the priest's household has the same status. This is a significant statement: the purchased slave's belonging to the priestly family overrides his non-priestly origin. The principle that membership matters more than birth is embedded in the Levitical system. It contrasts with the daughter who married a non-priest (v.12) — marriage out of the priestly household removes access, while purchase into it grants access.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A priest's daughter who marries a non-priest (<em>ish zar</em>) loses access to the sacred donations. Her status follows her husband's household — she has become part of a non-priestly economic unit. This rule reflects the ancient Israelite household structure where a woman's status was determined by her husband's household. The loss of terumah access was a real economic consequence of marriage outside the priestly family, not merely a ritual technicality.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The divorced or widowed daughter who returns to her father's house without children — having no living descendants from the non-priestly marriage — regains access to sacred donations. The condition 'with no children' is key: if she has children, they belong to the non-priestly line and she is presumed to be supporting them, not fully re-integrated into the priestly household. This nuanced rule shows careful attention to the actual family economics of ancient Israel.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The accidental eating of sacred donations by a layman requires restoration at full value plus a 20% surcharge (<em>chamishit</em>). This parallels the guilt offering regulations (Lev 5:14-16): trespass against the holy — even unintentional — requires real restitution. The 20% premium marks the special status of what was encroached upon. Second Temple halakha developed detailed rules about when and how laypersons might accidentally encounter <em>terumah</em> and their corresponding obligations.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'The priests shall not profane the holy things of the people of Israel, which they contribute to YHWH.' The priests bear responsibility not only for their own holiness but for protecting the integrity of the donation system on behalf of the whole people. If priests accept and eat donations improperly, they have profaned what the whole congregation brought to YHWH. This corporate responsibility of the priesthood is part of why the prophets reserved their sharpest critique for priestly corruption (Jer 2:8; Ezek 22:26; Mal 1:6-14).</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Causing them to bear iniquity and guilt, by eating their holy things' — the priest's profanation becomes the people's guilt. The sacrificial system was a system of covenant mediation: when the mediating priests corrupted the system, the whole covenant community suffered the consequences. The prophetic warnings about priestly failure (especially Malachi) are grounded in this principle: Israel's relationship with YHWH is damaged by priestly mishandling of its sacred institutions.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The transition to offering regulations (vv.17-25) addresses the quality of animals brought for burnt offerings and votive offerings. The <em>neder</em> (vow) and <em>nedavah</em> (freewill offering) represent two motivations for additional offerings beyond the required sacrifices: obligation fulfilled and spontaneous generosity. The <em>tamim</em> (perfect/without blemish) requirement applies to both — YHWH does not accept second-tier offerings regardless of the motivation behind them.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The law addresses offerings from 'the house of Israel or the sojourners in Israel' — resident non-Israelites could also bring offerings to YHWH's altar. This reflects the inclusive dimension of the tabernacle/temple as a place of access for all who aligned themselves with Israel's God. Numbers 15:15-16 makes this explicit: 'one statute for you and the stranger who sojourns among you.' The requirement that alien offerings also be <em>tamim</em> confirms that the standard transcends ethnic category.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'For your offering to be accepted it shall be a male without blemish of the cattle or the sheep or the goats.' The three livestock categories — cattle, sheep, goats — comprise the whole of the Israelite domesticated herd. The male requirement for burnt and votive offerings (females were permitted for some sin offerings, Lev 4:28, 32) reflected both the economic logic of herd management and the symbolic association of the male with strength and completeness.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Anything that has a blemish, you shall not offer, for it will not be acceptable for you.' The principle of acceptability (<em>ratzon</em>) is the governing criterion: YHWH's pleasure is not a given but depends on the integrity of the offering. Malachi 1:8 applies this directly: 'When you offer blind animals in sacrifice, is that not evil? And when you offer those that are lame or sick, is that not evil? Present that to your governor; will he accept you or show you favor?' The prophetic critique translates the Levitical standard into political-relational terms.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The peace offering (<em>shelamim</em>) for a vow or freewill offering must be <em>tamim</em> with no blemish. The <em>shelamim</em>'s communal character — portions to YHWH, priests, and offerer — meant that a blemished animal would have been consumed by the priestly family. The law protects the integrity of what the priests receive as well as what YHWH 'receives' (consumes in the altar fire). The whole offering economy depended on the <em>tamim</em> standard being maintained at every point.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The catalog of disqualifying conditions — blind, injured, maimed, with running sores, scabs, or scurvy — covers visible physical defects. The comprehensiveness of the list is designed to close any possible loophole for priestly discretion in accepting marginal animals. Compare with the Second Temple practice: the Mishnah (tractate Bekhorot) devotes extensive chapters to exactly which physical conditions constitute blemishes and which are within normal variation. The Levitical list generated centuries of legal interpretation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A freewill offering (<em>nedavah</em>) may be an ox or sheep with a limb too long or too short — a minor asymmetry that would disqualify for vowed offerings but is acceptable for the spontaneous offering. This distinction between vow fulfillment and freewill offering shows that the same blemish level does not apply equally to all offering types. The freewill offering's lower standard reflects its character as a gift from the heart; the vow fulfillment's stricter standard reflects that a made commitment must be fully honored.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The prohibition on offering bruised, crushed, torn, or cut animals extends the blemish rules to encompass human-caused alterations. Castration of animals was practiced in surrounding cultures for various agricultural purposes. The prohibition here ensures that the offering presented to YHWH has not been altered from its natural created state — it must be as it came from the Creator's hand. The same principle of natural integrity underlies the <em>tamim</em> requirement generally.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Neither shall you offer as the bread of your God any such animals bought from a foreigner. Since there is a blemish in them, a defect in them, they will not be accepted for you.' Even purchased foreign animals must meet the blemish-free standard. This confirms that the acceptability criterion is intrinsic to the animal, not to its source. The phrase 'bread of your God' (<em>lechem Elohekhem</em>) applies the offering vocabulary of the grain offering to animals, framing all altar offerings as YHWH's food — a common ancient Near Eastern conceptual framework that Leviticus employs while simultaneously differentiating YHWH from gods who 'need' food.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Newborn animals must remain with their mothers for seven days before being eligible for offering. The seven-day qualification period may reflect the natural bonding period observed between mother and offspring. It also parallels the human circumcision timing (eight days after birth) and the Sabbath pattern — the first seven-day cycle completes before the animal enters the world of religious obligation. This natural qualification period resists the pressure to offer immediately (perhaps from newly born animals given as freewill offerings) in favor of the rhythms of creation.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The law of mother-and-young not to be slaughtered on the same day (v.28) is here introduced with the seven-day waiting period for newborns. Both laws protect the natural mother-offspring relationship. Deuteronomy 22:6-7 (the bird's nest law) is a parallel: the mother bird must not be taken with the eggs. Both laws express a reverence for natural bonds that even the slaughter system must not gratuitously violate. The Mishnaic tractate Chullin and later responsa literature discuss these laws extensively.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'But you shall not kill an ox or a sheep and her young in one day.' The prohibition on same-day killing of mother and offspring is one of a handful of laws that recognize animal relationships in Levitical ethics. It is not anthropomorphism but a practical expression of the principle that creation's order is not to be carelessly disrupted. Later Jewish ethics (<em>tzaar ba'alei chayyim</em>, the prohibition on causing unnecessary animal suffering) grounds itself partly in this verse.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The thanksgiving offering (<em>toda</em>) regulations: it must be eaten on the day of sacrifice with nothing left until morning (v.30). The <em>toda</em> was the most situationally specific of the peace offerings — brought in response to a particular act of divine deliverance (Ps 107:22). Psalm 50:14-15 and 23 identify the <em>toda</em> as the offering YHWH most desires: 'offer to God a sacrifice of thanksgiving; call upon me in the day of trouble; I will deliver you, and you shall glorify me.' The same-day eating rule creates urgency and prevents the thanksgiving from being deferred or commercialized.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The same-day rule for the <em>toda</em> distinguishes it from the regular peace offering (which could be eaten over two days, Lev 7:15-16) and the freewill/vow offerings (which allowed a second day). The theological point: the thanksgiving must be consumed in the immediate context of the gratitude that prompted it. Gratitude has a shelf life; the law builds in the pastoral wisdom that acts of thanksgiving should be expressed while the sense of divine help is fresh and vivid.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'So you shall keep my commandments and do them: I am YHWH.' The dual verb <em>shamar</em> (keep/guard) and <em>asah</em> (do/perform) is the Holiness Code's standard covenant-obedience formula. Keeping means internalizing and guarding; doing means acting. The formula grounds all the specific regulations in the direct authority of YHWH's self-identification. The repeated 'I am YHWH' throughout chapters 18-26 (occurring over 40 times) functions as the non-negotiable authorization behind each law.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'And you shall not profane my holy name, that I may be sanctified among the people of Israel.' The concept of <em>kiddush hashem</em> (sanctifying the Name) and <em>chillul hashem</em> (profaning the Name) — articulated here more clearly than anywhere else in the Torah — became foundational for Jewish ethics. YHWH's reputation among Israel and the nations is a stake in every act of covenant faithfulness or unfaithfulness. Ezekiel develops this extensively (Ezek 36:20-23): Israel's exile profaned YHWH's name among the nations; the new covenant restoration will vindicate it. The concept underlies Paul's lament in Romans 2:24 ('the name of God is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you') and the Lord's Prayer ('hallowed be your name').</p>",
    "33": "<p>'I am YHWH who sanctifies you, who brought you out of the land of Egypt to be your God: I am YHWH.' The closing formula anchors the holiness requirements in the Exodus narrative. Israel's distinctive practices are the response to YHWH's prior saving act — not the condition of it. The sequence is always redemption first (Exod 1-18), then covenant obligation (Exod 19-Lev). This Exodus-grounding of ethics appears across the Torah (Exod 20:2 precedes the Decalogue; Deut 6:21-25 connects commandments to the Exodus) and is fundamental to understanding how Levitical holiness works.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 23 presents the most complete festival calendar in the Torah. Three other festival calendars appear in the Pentateuch (Exod 23:14-17; Exod 34:18-26; Deut 16:1-17), each with different emphases, but Leviticus 23 is the fullest, including Trumpets (Rosh HaShanah) and Yom Kippur that the earlier calendars omit. The chapter organizes Israel's year theologically: time itself belongs to YHWH, and his appointments (<em>moadim</em>) structure the annual cycle. The NT reads this calendar as a typological program whose fulfillments cluster in the life of Christ and the church.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'The appointed feasts of YHWH (<em>moadei YHWH</em>) which you shall proclaim as holy convocations, they are my appointed feasts.' The possessive 'my' is emphatic: these are YHWH's feasts, not merely Israel's religious calendar. The verb 'proclaim' (<em>tiqreu</em>) makes the calendar a matter of public announcement — the new moon had to be sighted and declared by the Sanhedrin in Second Temple Judaism, after which bonfires were lit across the hilltops to carry the news. The precise timing of feasts depended on this proclamation chain.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Sabbath heads the festival calendar as the paradigmatic and most frequent <em>moed</em>. Unlike the annual feasts, the Sabbath is not tied to agriculture or history but to creation itself (Gen 2:1-3; Exod 20:11). Its position at the head of the calendar signals that all the annual festivals are extensions of the Sabbath principle: YHWH claims regular intervals of time as sacred. The phrase <em>shabbat shabbaton</em> (intense rest, rest-upon-rest) marks the Sabbath as the foundational rest from which all others derive their logic.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The transition phrase 'these are the appointed feasts of YHWH, the holy convocations, which you shall proclaim at their appointed time' formally opens the annual calendar distinct from the weekly Sabbath. The stress on 'appointed time' (<em>bemoadam</em>) reflects the calendrical precision of the system: each festival must occur at its designated point in the agricultural and sacred year. The proclamation function meant Israel's calendar was not merely observed but announced — it was a public, communal, maintained institution.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Passover (<em>Pesach</em>) on the 14th of the first month at twilight (<em>bein ha-arbayim</em>, between the evenings) is the foundational festival, recalling Israel's deliverance from Egypt (Exod 12). In the Second Temple period, hundreds of thousands of pilgrims gathered in Jerusalem for Passover — Josephus estimates figures suggesting the city's population swelled enormously. The Passover lamb was killed in the temple precincts on the afternoon of the 14th, and families consumed it that night (the beginning of the 15th). John's Gospel places the crucifixion on the day of Passover preparation (John 19:14), making Jesus the Passover lamb killed as the lambs were killed.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The seven-day Festival of Unleavened Bread (<em>Chag haMatzot</em>) beginning on the 15th immediately follows Passover. The removal of leaven (<em>chametz</em>) from all households — a major domestic operation — combined the festival with a thorough household cleaning. The seven-day duration created a full week of consecration following the Passover night. Paul's allegorization (1 Cor 5:7-8) — 'cleanse out the old leaven... Christ our Passover has been sacrificed' — works within this Passover-Matzot complex, reading the household leaven-removal as a metaphor for personal moral transformation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The first day of Unleavened Bread is a holy convocation with no servile work — a Sabbath-like day within the festival. The <em>melechet avodah</em> (servile/laborious work) prohibition on festival days allowed food preparation (Exod 12:16) but not ordinary occupational labor. This created a festive rhythm distinct from both ordinary weekdays and the full Sabbath rest. Second Temple halakha debated the boundaries of what constituted <em>melechet avodah</em>, resulting in the tractate Beitzah/Yom Tov.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Special burnt offerings for each day of Unleavened Bread (detailed in Num 28:17-25) supplemented the daily <em>tamid</em> offerings throughout the festival week. The seventh day also had a holy convocation with no servile work. The bracketing structure — holy convocation at start and end, special offerings throughout — surrounded the week with consecrated time while the daily life of food preparation continued inside it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The wave-sheaf offering (vv.9-14) introduces the firstfruits section — the agricultural ceremony that inaugurated the grain harvest season and opened a 49-day count to Shavuot. The Omer offering was the 'official' start of barley harvest; until it was waved before YHWH, the new grain could not be consumed (v.14). The agricultural calendar of ancient Israel depended heavily on the spring barley harvest (March-April) followed by the wheat harvest (May-June), with the Omer bridging between them.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'When you come into the land that I give you and reap its harvest, you shall bring the sheaf of the firstfruits of your harvest to the priest.' The firstfruits obligation is explicitly tied to possession of the land — it was not applicable in the wilderness but came into force upon Israel's settlement in Canaan. The law is both theological (the land belongs to YHWH who gives its produce) and agrarian (the first of the harvest acknowledges dependence on the Creator-giver). Ruth 2 dramatizes the harvest season during which the Omer would have been offered.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'He shall wave the sheaf before YHWH, so that you may be accepted. On the day after the Sabbath the priest shall wave it.' The disputed phrase <em>mimocharat hashabbat</em> (on the day after the Sabbath) became the center of a calendrical controversy that split Second Temple Judaism: Pharisees read 'Sabbath' as the high-day Sabbath of Passover week (always the 15th of Nisan), making the wave-sheaf always on the 16th; Sadducees/Karaites read it as the weekly Sabbath within Passover week, making the count always start on a Sunday. If the Sadducean reading is correct, the resurrection (first Sunday after Passover), the wave-sheaf, and Pentecost all fall on Sundays by design.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The burnt offering accompanying the wave-sheaf — a year-old male lamb without blemish — was the dedication of the harvest's firstfruits to YHWH. The grain and drink offerings accompanying it (v.13) created a complete offering complex: animal, grain, and liquid all presented together. The inclusion of a burnt offering with the wave-sheaf elevated the agricultural ceremony into a full worship event, not merely a calendrical marker.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The grain offering (<em>minchah</em>) of two-tenths of an ephah of fine flour mixed with oil, and a drink offering of wine — the standard accompanying gifts for a burnt offering (cf. Num 15:1-12, which systematizes the accompanying offerings by animal size). The combination of grain and wine with the burnt offering creates a full-spectrum offering: animal life (the lamb), agricultural produce (grain), and the fruit of cultivation (wine) are all dedicated to YHWH at the firstfruits ceremony.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'You shall eat neither bread nor grain parched or fresh until this very day, until you have brought the offering of your God.' The pre-Omer prohibition on new grain created a national fast from the harvest until the firstfruits offering — every household in Israel was dependent on the temple ceremony to 'release' the new harvest for consumption. This structural dependence on the priestly cult was deliberate: the food supply itself was framed as YHWH's gift, accessed only through proper acknowledgment of the Giver.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'You shall count seven full weeks from the day after the Sabbath, from the day that you brought the wave offering of the sheaf.' The 49-day counting period — <em>Sefirat HaOmer</em> (counting of the Omer) — creates a daily discipline of anticipation between Passover/Firstfruits and Shavuot/Pentecost. In rabbinic tradition, the counting period from redemption (Passover) to revelation (Torah given at Sinai) became a time of spiritual preparation, mourning, and self-examination — a theological journey from the Exodus to Sinai.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'You shall count fifty days to the day after the seventh Sabbath. Then you shall present a grain offering of new wheat to YHWH.' The fiftieth day — <em>Shavuot</em> in Hebrew, <em>Pentecost</em> (fiftieth) in Greek — marked the end of the wheat harvest and the beginning of a new agricultural season. Acts 2:1-4 places the outpouring of the Holy Spirit at Pentecost, reading the festival as the appropriate moment for YHWH's new covenant 'harvest' — the Spirit's first ingathering of the new covenant community from 'every nation under heaven' (Acts 2:5).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The two leavened wave loaves at Shavuot are unique: virtually every other grain offering at the altar was unleavened (Lev 2:11), but the Pentecost offering uses leavened bread. Some interpreters read the two loaves as representing Israel and the Gentiles who would be incorporated at Pentecost (Acts 2), both brought before YHWH in their actual fermented/imperfect state. Others read the leaven simply as indicating fully processed harvest bread — the culmination of the harvest process from raw grain to baked loaf. The two loaves are baked offerings, not mere grain — the full harvest cycle completed.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The accompanying burnt offerings at Shavuot — seven male lambs, one bull, two rams — plus sin and peace offerings (vv.18-19) represent the fullest sacrificial complex in the festival calendar. Numbers 28:26-31 gives a parallel accounting. The scale of the Shavuot offerings reflects the significance of the day: the completion of the grain harvest was a major agricultural and religious event. In the Second Temple period, the <em>bikurim</em> (firstfruits basket of Deut 26) was also brought at Shavuot, creating an elaborate festive occasion.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The sin offering (<em>chattat</em>) and peace offerings (<em>shelamim</em>) at Shavuot follow the major burnt offering complex. The inclusion of a sin offering at this joyful harvest festival reflects the Levitical principle that approach to YHWH always involves purification — no celebration is purely celebratory without atonement. The peace offerings then enable a communal meal of celebration: the two loaves waved before YHWH become priestly food (v.20), shared in the holy space of the tabernacle/temple.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'The priest shall wave them with the bread of the firstfruits as a wave offering before YHWH, with the two lambs. They shall be holy to YHWH for the priest.' The wave offering (<em>tenufah</em>) brings the offering into YHWH's sphere and then gives it to the priests — a liturgical gesture that enacts the triangular economy of the system: Israel offers → YHWH receives → YHWH gives to priests (1 Cor 9:13-14 draws on precisely this logic).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Shavuot holy convocation with no servile work follows the same pattern as Unleavened Bread (v.7-8) and anticipates Trumpets, Yom Kippur, and Sukkot. The festival days are structurally parallel: all involve the sacred assembly, suspended servile labor, special offerings, and the sanctification of Israel's time by YHWH's claim. The repetition of the structure creates a calendar-wide rhythm that Israel rehearses seven times in the annual cycle.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The gleaning laws for the poor and the sojourner appear unexpectedly in the middle of the festival calendar (parallel to Lev 19:9-10 and Deut 24:19-21). Their insertion here is interpretively significant: the festival of harvest thanksgiving (Shavuot) is incomplete without explicit provision for the poor. The agricultural surplus that enables festival celebration must be shared with those who have no harvest of their own. Ruth dramatizes this law: the Shavuot-season harvest at Bethlehem is the backdrop for Boaz's generous gleaning allowances for Ruth the Moabite stranger.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'YHWH spoke to Moses, saying...' — the standard revelation formula reintroduces each new law section. Its repetition throughout Leviticus marks each unit as a discrete divine speech act, not a continuous human composition. The formula also keeps Moses visible as the human mediator through whom these laws reach Israel, grounding the legal corpus in the Sinai encounter.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Feast of Trumpets on the first of the seventh month (<em>Tishri</em>). The seventh month is the most festival-dense: Trumpets (1st), Yom Kippur (10th), Sukkot (15th-21st), and Shemini Atzeret (22nd). The concentration of festivals in the seventh month mirrors the sanctity of the seventh day (Sabbath) and the seventh year (Sabbatical). The shofar blast (<em>teruah</em>) that defines the day was also used in battle, at coronations, and at divine appearances — calling both Israel to attention and YHWH to remembrance.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Trumpets is a holy convocation with no servile work and special offerings (Num 29:1-6). In Second Temple Judaism the day was increasingly associated with divine judgment and the opening of the heavenly books (the imagery developed in post-biblical texts like 1 Enoch). Later Judaism named the day <em>Rosh HaShanah</em> (Head of the Year) — though the Torah calls it the first of the seventh month, not the first of the year. The tension between the agricultural new year (spring, Nisan) and the civil new year (fall, Tishri) reflects two different but legitimate ways of reckoning the annual cycle.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'YHWH spoke to Moses, saying...' — the formal speech introduction recurs, marking Yom Kippur as a separate divine instruction. The position of Yom Kippur between Trumpets and Sukkot creates a penitential preparation for the festival season: Trumpets sounds the alarm (judgment is near), Yom Kippur provides atonement, and Sukkot celebrates restoration and provision. This 'Days of Awe' structure (<em>Yamim Nora'im</em>, the ten days between Trumpets and Yom Kippur) became the center of the Jewish spiritual year.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'On the tenth day of this seventh month is the Day of Atonement. It shall be for you a time of holy convocation, and you shall afflict yourselves (<em>initem et nafshoteichem</em>).' The affliction of the soul — understood as fasting from sundown to sundown — became the defining physical practice of Yom Kippur. In Second Temple Judaism the high priest's elaborate entrance into the holy of holies on this day was the most sacred moment of the religious year. When the temple was destroyed in 70 CE the entire Yom Kippur sacrificial system became inoperative; rabbinic Judaism pivoted to prayer, fasting, and repentance as substitutes.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'You shall not do any work on that very day, for it is a Day of Atonement, to make atonement for you before YHWH your God.' Yom Kippur's work prohibition (<em>kol melacha</em>, all work) is the strictest in the calendar — not the milder <em>melechet avodah</em> of other festival days, but total cessation as on the Sabbath. This full Sabbath character was reinforced by the 'shabbat shabbaton' designation (v.32). Hebrews reads the annual Yom Kippur ritual as the proof of the inadequacy of the Levitical system: its annual repetition demonstrated that the sin problem had not been permanently solved (Heb 10:1-4).</p>",
    "29": "<p><em>Karet</em> (cutting off) for not afflicting the soul on Yom Kippur is the most unusual <em>karet</em> application in the Torah: most <em>karet</em> penalties attach to violations of active prohibitions (eating blood, uncovering nakedness, etc.); here it attaches to failure to observe a positive fasting requirement. This confirms that the atonement of Yom Kippur was not merely something done by the high priest on Israel's behalf without Israel's participation — the whole covenant community was obligated to actively receive it through fasting and affliction.</p>",
    "30": "<p>YHWH will also 'destroy' (<em>vehibadeti</em>) the person who works on Yom Kippur — a divine enforcement added to the community enforcement of <em>karet</em>. The double sanction (communal excision + divine destruction) signals the unique gravity of Yom Kippur. The day was meant to be the national moment of confession, atonement, and covenant renewal; treating it like an ordinary workday was a fundamental rejection of the covenant relationship.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'You shall not do any work. It is a statute forever throughout your generations in all your dwelling places.' The universality clause — 'in all your dwelling places' — extends Yom Kippur beyond the tabernacle/temple to every Jewish household in every location. The festival observances were not only temple events but domestic ones: while the sacrificial component required the sanctuary, the fasting, affliction, and rest could be observed anywhere. This diaspora applicability became critical after the temple's destruction.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'It is a Sabbath of solemn rest to you, and you shall afflict yourselves. On the ninth day of the month beginning at evening, from evening to evening shall you keep your Sabbath.' The Yom Kippur fast runs from sunset on the 9th to nightfall on the 10th — the only twenty-five-hour fast in the biblical calendar. The specification of the sunset-to-nightfall boundary reflects the Levitical understanding that the day runs from evening to evening (Gen 1). The intensive <em>shabbat shabbaton</em> applied to Yom Kippur elevates it to the supreme Sabbath of the year.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'YHWH spoke to Moses, saying...' — the third speech-introduction formula in chapter 23 introduces Sukkot, the longest and most elaborate festival section. Sukkot receives more space than any other festival in this chapter, reflecting its importance as the great harvest celebration at the end of the agricultural year. In Second Temple Judaism, Sukkot was the pilgrimage festival that drew the largest crowds to Jerusalem (cf. 1 Kgs 8:2 — Solomon dedicated the temple at Sukkot; John 7-8 — Jesus's Jerusalem ministry occurs during Sukkot).</p>",
    "34": "<p>'On the fifteenth day of this seventh month and for seven days is the Feast of Booths (<em>Chag haSukkot</em>) to YHWH.' Sukkot begins on the 15th of Tishri, five days after Yom Kippur — the most dramatic emotional transition in the Jewish calendar: from the gravity and austerity of the Day of Atonement to the joy and celebration of the harvest festival. This juxtaposition is theologically intentional: atonement cleared the way for celebration. The rabbis call Sukkot <em>zman simchatenu</em> (the season of our rejoicing), connecting its joy to the secure standing with YHWH achieved at Yom Kippur.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The first day of Sukkot is a holy convocation with no servile work — the opening Sabbath-day of the festival. The full offering complex for Sukkot (Num 29:13-34) is the most extensive in the annual calendar: 70 bulls total over the seven days, decreasing each day. Jewish tradition connected the 70 bulls to the 70 nations of the world (Gen 10), interpreting Sukkot as Israel's intercessory sacrifice for all humanity — a universalist dimension to the festival.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The eighth day (<em>Shemini Atzeret</em>, solemn closing assembly) follows the seven days of Sukkot as a separate but attached holy day. The <em>atzeret</em> (gathering/holding back) is the festival's formal close — the day that seals the entire festival season before ordinary time resumes. John 7:37-38 places Jesus's proclamation of living water on 'the last day, the great day of the feast' — almost certainly referring either to <em>Hoshana Rabbah</em> (the seventh day of Sukkot, when the water-libation ceremony reached its climax in Second Temple practice) or to <em>Shemini Atzeret</em> itself.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'These are the appointed feasts of YHWH, which you shall proclaim as times of holy convocation, for presenting to YHWH food offerings (<em>isheh</em>), burnt offerings and grain offerings, sacrifices and drink offerings, each on its proper day.' The summary verse inventories the full offering repertoire: the complete range of Israel's worship vocabulary was brought into play at the festivals. No one type of offering alone served all the relational dimensions of the festival; the variety expressed the multidimensional character of Israel's covenant relationship with YHWH.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'Besides the Sabbaths of YHWH and besides your gifts and besides all your vow offerings and besides all your freewill offerings which you give to YHWH' — the festival offerings are presented as additional to, not replacing, the regular Sabbath and daily offerings. The festival system layered additional offerings on top of the baseline <em>tamid</em> (perpetual daily offering) and weekly Sabbath offerings. The worship economy of the Second Temple operated these multiple offering streams simultaneously, requiring an enormous ongoing supply of animals, grain, oil, wine, and priestly labor.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'On the fifteenth day of the seventh month, when you have gathered in the produce of the land, you shall celebrate the feast of YHWH seven days.' The agricultural grounding of Sukkot is explicit: it follows the ingathering of crops (<em>be'asphekhem et tevuat ha-aretz</em>). The Israelite agricultural calendar ended with the olive and grape harvests in early autumn; Sukkot celebrated the completion of the entire harvest year. Both agricultural calendar and sacred calendar were YHWH's — the land's produce and the year's time belonged to the same Creator who redeemed Israel from Egypt.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The four species (<em>arba'at ha-minim</em>) — fruit of splendid trees (<em>etrog</em>/citron), palm branches (<em>lulav</em>), boughs of leafy trees (myrtle), and willows of the brook — are taken and used for rejoicing before YHWH. The binding of the four species into the Sukkot bundle and waving it in all directions (indicating YHWH's presence everywhere) became one of the most distinctive Jewish ritual acts. In Second Temple Jerusalem, the lulav-waving during the Hallel psalms and the water-libation ceremony made Sukkot a visually spectacular festival.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Sukkot is to be 'a statute forever throughout your generations' (<em>chuqqat olam leDoroteichem</em>). The <em>chok</em> (statute) designation — marking a law whose rationale is not stated — precedes the explanation (v.43), suggesting that obedience is expected before comprehension. The seven-day duration mirrors the creation week, with the eighth day (<em>Shemini Atzeret</em>) corresponding to the new beginning beyond the seven. Zechariah 14:16-19 projects Sukkot celebration into the eschatological future: all nations will come to Jerusalem to keep Sukkot in the age to come.</p>",
    "42": "<p>'You shall dwell in booths for seven days. All native Israelites shall dwell in booths.' The requirement to actually live in the booths — not merely decorate them — was meant to create the experience of temporary dwelling for every Israelite family. The material simplicity of the sukkah (a structure open to the sky) enforced the vulnerable-dependency feeling that YHWH intended the wilderness memorial to evoke. All Israelites, wealthy or poor, spent seven days in the same kind of temporary structure — a leveling institution in the annual calendar.</p>",
    "43": "<p>'That your generations may know that I made the people of Israel dwell in booths when I brought them out of the land of Egypt: I am YHWH your God.' The theological rationale of Sukkot: the booths are a memorial of the wilderness period, when Israel lived in temporary structures entirely dependent on YHWH for provision (manna, water from rock, pillar of cloud). Annual booth-dwelling prevents amnesia about Israel's foundational neediness and YHWH's foundational faithfulness. The <em>lema'an yeda'u</em> formula ('that they may know') is a recurring Exodus-knowledge pattern: ritual acts encode theological knowledge for transmission across generations.</p>",
    "44": "<p>'Thus Moses declared to the people of Israel the appointed feasts of YHWH.' The chapter closes with Moses as the formal mediator who communicates YHWH's appointments to Israel. The entire festival calendar is framed as a received tradition, not a human construction: YHWH set the times, Moses declared them, Israel observes them. The NT reads the festival calendar fulfillment in the same way: the appointments were YHWH's from the beginning, Christ their fulfillment on schedule. 1 Corinthians 5:7-8 (Passover/Matzot), 1 Corinthians 15:20-23 (Firstfruits), Acts 2:1-4 (Pentecost), and Hebrews 9-10 (Yom Kippur) together constitute a systematic NT reading of the Levitical calendar.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(existing, LEVITICUS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus', existing)
    for ch in ['22', '23']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with context commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
